ce:section.ce:para:
The projected density of states (PDOS; Fig. 5
                        ) shows that the HOMO and LUMO levels of the nanocomposites are dominated by the state of the GQD, with the cellulose state located deep within the valence band (VB) and conduction band (CB) of the nanocomposites. The calculated PDOS values are consistent with the experimental observation that the GQD@cellulose nanocomposites can be used as fluorescent probes for the detection of Fe3+ (Lv et al., 2019), because when the HOMO or LUMO level is dominated by the cellulose states, this leads to photoluminescence quenching of the GQDs, which defeats the purpose of using GQD@cellulose nanocomposites as fluorescence probes. Except for GQD-z-t@cellulose, the HOMO states are distributed over the surface and edges of the GQDs in the nanocomposites. In the case of GQD-z-t@cellulose, a significant fraction of the HOMO states is located at the GQD edges (Fig. 6
                        ), consistent with the findings of Abdelsalam et al. (2018). Moreover, the HOMO level of the GQD is higher than that of cellulose. Therefore, due to the unfavorable energy alignment, the photoexcited holes cannot be extracted from the VBs of the GQDs and transferred to the cellulose. Similarly, the photoexcited electrons cannot be transferred from the CBs of the GQDs to the cellulose in the nanocomposites studied herein because the LUMO levels of the GQDs are energetically lower than those of the cellulose. Such energy alignments are not beneficial for charge separation in GQD@cellulose nanocomposites and result in low energy conversion efficiencies.
